\section{Questions to be handed in for project 7:}\newline
To get started, we load the \texttt{Gadfly} backend for \texttt{Plots} so that we can make plots, and the \texttt{Roots} package for its \texttt{D} and \texttt{fzero} functionality:\begin{verbatim}
using Plots
gadfly()
using Roots			
\end{verbatim}
\subsubsection{Quick background}\newline
Read about this material here: \href{http://mth229.github.io/first-second-derivatives.html}{Exploring first and second derivatives with Julia}.\newline
For the impatient, this assignment looks at the relationship between a function, $f(x)$, and its first and second derivatives, $f'(x)$ and $f''(x)$. The basic relationship can be summarized (though the devil is in the details) by:\newline
\texttt{*} if the first derivative is \textit{positive} on $(a,b)$ then the function   is \textit{increasing} on $(a,b)$.\newline
\texttt{*} If the second derivative is \textit{positive} on $(a,b)$ then the function   is \textit{concave up} on $(a,b)$.\newline
(The devil here is that the converse statements are not quite always true.)\newline
We can use the \texttt{D} operator from the \texttt{Roots} package to find the first and second derivatives of \texttt{f}. Recall, if \texttt{f} is a function, then \texttt{D(f)} will be a function that computes its \textit{first} derivative and \texttt{D(f,2)} will be a function that computes its \textit{second} derivative. If you define this function (ignoring any warnings):\begin{verbatim}
Base.ctranspose(f::Function) = D(f)
\end{verbatim}
\begin{verbatim}
ctranspose (generic function with 53 methods)\end{verbatim}
\newline
then you can use \texttt{f'} instead of \texttt{D(f)} and \texttt{f''} in place of \texttt{D(f,2)}.\newline
In the notes, the following function is used to plot a function \texttt{f} using two colors depending on whether the second function, \texttt{g} is positive or not.\begin{verbatim}
function plotif(f, g, a, b)
  plot([f, x -> g(x) > 0.0 ? f(x) : NaN], a, b, linewidth=5)
end
\end{verbatim}
\begin{verbatim}
plotif (generic function with 1 method)\end{verbatim}
\newline
This allows a graphical exploration of the above facts. For example, using it like this: \texttt{plotif(f,f', a, b)} will show a different color when $f(x)$ is \textit{increasing} whereas \texttt{plotif(f,f,a,b)} will show a different color when $f(x)$ is \textit{positive}.\rule{\textwidth}{1pt}
\newline
As a reminder\newline
\texttt{*} a \textit{critical} point of $f$ is a value in the domain of $f(x)$ for which the derivative is $0$ or undefined. These are often but \textbf{not always} where $f(x)$ has a local maximum or minimum. \newline
\texttt{*} An \textit{inflection point} of $f$ is a value in the domain of $f(x)$ where the concavity of $f$ changes. (These are \textit{often} but \textbf{not always} where $f''(x)=0$.)\newline
We can graphically identify these points or find them numerically by finding zeroes of the appropriate function.  To find zeros we have the function call \texttt{fzero(f, a)} to find a zero iteratively starting at $x=a$ or \texttt{fzeros(f, [a,b])} to naively search for any zeros in the interval $[a,b]$.  (Recall, \texttt{fzeros} may miss some values, so a graph should always be made to double check)\newline
For example:\begin{verbatim}
f(x) = 1 + cos(x) + cos(2x)
fzero(f, 1.5)
\end{verbatim}
\begin{verbatim}
1.5707963267948966\end{verbatim}
\newline
Or to get all values in an interval:\begin{verbatim}
zs = fzeros(f, [0, 2pi])
\end{verbatim}
\begin{verbatim}
4-element Array{Float64,1}:
 1.5708 
 2.0944 
 4.18879
 4.71239\end{verbatim}
\newline
The answer from \texttt{fzeros} is a vector of values. You can get individual ones different way or work with them all at once. For example, here is the derivative's value at each point:\begin{verbatim}
map(f', zs)
\end{verbatim}
\begin{verbatim}
4-element Array{Float64,1}:
 -1.0     
  0.866025
 -0.866025
  1.0     \end{verbatim}
\newline
In addition, there are two main derivative tests:\newline
\texttt{*} The \textbf{first derivative test}:  This states that for a differentiable function $f(x)$ with a critical point at $c$ then if $f'(x)$ changes sign from $+$ to $-$ at $c$ then $f(c)$ is a local maximum and if it changes sign from $-$ to $+$ then $f(c)$ is a local minimum.\newline
\texttt{*} The \textbf{second derivative test}: This states that if $c$ is a critical point of $f(x)$ and $f''(c) > 0$ then $f(c)$ is a local minimum and if $f''(c) < 0$ then $f(c)$ is a local maximum.\subsubsection{Questions}\subsubsection{Graphical explorations}\begin{itemize}\item The \texttt{airy} function is a \textit{built-in} function that is important for   some applications. \subsubsection{Concave up has alternate definitions}\newline
The Rogawski book defines $f(x)$ to be concave up for differentiable functions by: \begin{quotation}$f(x)$\newline
is concave up on $(a,b)$ if $f'(x)$ is increasing on $(a,b)$.\end{quotation}\newline
But, not all functions have derivatives. For \textit{continuous} functions, an alternate definition of concave up on $(a,b)$ is that for any pair of points, $(c,d)$ with $a < c < d < b$ the function value at the average is less than or equal the average of the function values:
$$
f(\frac{c + d}{2}) \leq \frac{f(c) + f(d)}{2}
$$
\begin{itemize}\item Verify that this holds for the continuous, concave up function $f(x) = e^x$ by picking two values for $c$ and $d$ and checking the inequality. Show your commands.\end{itemize}
\\begin{answer}
type: longtext
reminder: Commands to verify f((a+b)/2 <= (f(a) + f(b))/2 for e^x
answer_text: f(x) = exp(x)
c,d = rand(2)
f((c+d)/2) <= (f(c) + f(d))/2
 
rows: 3
cols: 60
\\end{answer}
\newline
For any function, \href{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_function}{Wikipedia} gives a different definition which basically says $f(x)$ is concave up on $(a,b)$ if for \textbf{any} pair of points, $c$ and $d$ with $a < c < d < b$ the has the secant line connecting $(c,f(c))$ and $(d,f(d))$ lies \textit{above} the graph of $f(x)$ over $(c,d)$.\newline
This can be investigated graphically. This function is helpful for making a secant line:\begin{verbatim}
function secline(f, c, d)
  x0, y0, m = c, f(c), (f(c) - f(d)) / (c - d)
  x -> y0 + m * (x - x0)	# pt-slope form as function
end
\end{verbatim}
\begin{verbatim}
secline (generic function with 1 method)\end{verbatim}
\newline
For a function, say, $f(x) = \sin(x)$, it is used as:\begin{verbatim}
f(x)=sin(x)
plot([f, secline(f, pi/6, pi/3)], 0, pi/2)
\end{verbatim}
\begin{html}
<img alt="Embedded Image" src="data:image/png;base64,">

\end{html}
\newline
That makes a graph of $\sin(x)$ over $[0, \pi/2]$ and draws the secant line between $[\pi/6, \pi/3]$. This line lies \textit{below} the graph of $f(x)$, so we can say definitively that $\sin(x)$ is \textit{not} concave up over $[0, \pi/2]$. (It is concave down.)\newline
